related_questions.question: Do alliums come back every year?
related_questions.snippet: Do alliums come back every year? Alliums are perennials so if they are planted in a well-suited environment they will not only bloom beautifully for the first year, they will return year after year.
related_questions.title: Everything you need to know about Allium Bulbs - DutchGrown

related_questions.question: Why avoid Allium?
related_questions.snippet: For example, someone with an allium intolerance may suffer from cramping or diarrhoea after eating garlic or leeks, while for someone with a diagnosed onion allergy, symptoms could include difficulty breathing and even anaphylaxis.
related_questions.title: Allium Intolerance | Symptoms and Testing - YorkTest

related_questions.question: Do alliums like full sun or shade?
related_questions.snippet: Light: Allium thrive in full sun, but can tolerate part-shade conditions. Soil: A well-drained soil is the most important condition for allium as bulbs may rot if left in wet soil. The average soil of most garden beds kept moist but not wet is generally fine.
related_questions.title: full sun

related_questions.question: Is Allium the same as garlic?
related_questions.snippet: Allium. Sound familiar? Unless you are fluent in Latin it probably won't, because Allium is the Latin word for garlic. In biology, Allium is the designation for a genus of plants that includes not just garlic, but onions, shallots, leeks, scallions, and chives as well.
related_questions.title: All About Alliums

buttons.subtitle: Where Does Allium Grow
buttons.title: How to Grow Alliums | BBC Gardeners World Magazine
buttons.snippet: Alliums do best in a sunny spot in a very well-drained soil. They're not fussy about soil type. Plant taller varieties towards the back of a border and shorter-growing types in the front. Alliums are well suited to growing in pots but their strappy foliage can look unsightly after flowering.
snippet_highlighted_words: a sunny spot in a very well-drained soil

buttons.subtitle: Is Allium Edible?
buttons.title: Edible alliums / RHS Gardening
buttons.snippet: Edible alliums are really useful in the kitchen, they include versatile vegetables such as onions (Allium cepa), shallots (Allium cepa Aggregatum Group), garlic, and leeks and herbs such as, chives (Allium schoenoprasum) and wild garlic (Allium ursinum) which make great garnishes in salads, soups and many other dishes.
snippet_highlighted_words: Edible alliums are really useful in the kitchen

buttons.subtitle: Is Allium Invasive
buttons.title: How to grow and plant alliums for your spring and summer garden
buttons.snippet: Not all alliums are welcome in the garden; some are invasive weeds that can be difficult to get rid of. Allium ursinum Also known as wild garlic or damsons, they may look pretty in the dappled light of woodland but in the garden the plant will spread rapidly by seed and bulbil and smother less vigorous plants.
snippet_highlighted_words: some are invasive weeds that can be difficult to get rid of

buttons.title: Allium 101: A guide to onions, garlic, leeks, chives & more
buttons.snippet: While all alliums taste like onions or garlic to some degree, each has its own unique flavor and texture. Most alliums are at their peak during spring and summer in Tennessee.
snippet_highlighted_words: onions or garlic to some degree

buttons.subtitle: What Are The Health Benefits Of Alliums
buttons.title: Allium Flavonols: Health Benefits, Molecular Targets, and Bioavailability
buttons.snippet: The bioactive compounds in alliums mainly include organosulfur compounds, polyphenols, dietary fibers, and saponins. Flavonoids, particularly flavonols from alliums, have been demonstrated to have the antioxidant, anticancer, hypolipidemic, anti-diabetic, cardioprotective, neuroprotective, and antimicrobial activities.
snippet_highlighted_words: antioxidant, anticancer, hypolipidemic, anti-diabetic, cardioprotective, neuroprotective, and antimicrobial activities

buttons.subtitle: When Does Allium Grow?
buttons.title: Planting allium bulbs in the garden and in containers. - DutchGrown
buttons.snippet: They should be planted in fall between September and November, before the soil freezes. You will rarely have to worry about watering them as they actually prefer dry conditions. Choose a sunny spot, water them when you plant them and then just wait for the lovely blooms in late spring and early summer.

buttons.subtitle: How To Plant And Grow Allium
buttons.title: How to Plant, Grow and Care for Alliums - DutchGrown
buttons.snippet: Pick a spot in your garden that has well-draining soil and gets full sun. Plant the allium bulbs about 4-8” deep and 6-8” apart, placing them in the ground with their pointy ends up. Water well once and wait for spring. After the alliums have bloomed don't cut off the foliage.

buttons.subtitle: Stages Of Allium
buttons.title: Allium Growth Stages - Sustainable Market Farming
buttons.snippet: The botanical group of bulb onions includes scallions (spring onions, salad onions or escallions), and the small pickling onions (cipollini). They have three distinct phases of growth — vegetative, bulbing and blooming (bolting) The switch from one phase to the next is triggered by environmental factors.

buttons.subtitle: How Long Do Allium Bulbs Last?
buttons.title: Everything you need to know about Allium Bulbs - DutchGrown
buttons.snippet: It is best to plant taller varieties near the back of the border to help with stabilising them. Check out our guide on growing alliums in borders. How many years do alliums last? Alliums are perennials so will last many years but will need to be divided every 3-4 years.
